Problem 1

Part a

# Assume user has crowdedness.csv in their working directory.
fpath <- paste0(getwd(), "/crowdedness.csv")
dat <- read.csv(fpath, header = T, sep = ",")

# Group by day of week and find the sum for each of the groups.
days_amount <- aggregate(dat$number_people,
  by = list(dat$day_of_week),
  FUN = sum
)
# Extract frequency column and convert to table
tab <- as.table(days_amount$x)
# Give levels interpretable names
names(tab) <- c("M", "Tu", "W", "Th", "F", "Sa", "Su")

test <- chisq.test(tab)
# p-value < 2.2e-16 so we reject the null hypothesis

# Reset plot settings to default
par(
  mar = c(5.1, 4.1, 4.1, 2.1),
  mfrow = c(1, 1)
)
# It is now evident that the seven days of the week are not equally crowded both from the below plot and the above p-value.
# Plot histogram of observed vs expected
barplot(rbind(tab, test$expected),
  beside = T,
  xlab = "Day of the Week",
  ylab = "Total Attendence",
  ylim = c(0, 400000),
  main = "Gym Attendence",
  legend = c("Observed", "Expected")
)

Part b

Here we consider the relationship between month and attendance. H0 is all month have equal amount of people(equally crowded). Note that since the datafile does not contain a equal number of each month, we only consider the data in the complete year of 2016 so every month only appears once

dat2016 = dat[13571:59117, ]
month_amount <- aggregate(dat2016$number_people,
                         by = list(dat2016$month),
                         FUN = sum
)
tab <- as.table(month_amount$x)
names(tab) <- c("Jan", "Feb", "Mar", "Apr", "Mar", "Jun", 
                "Jul", "Aug", "Sep", "Oct", "Nov", "Dec" )
test <- chisq.test(tab)
# p-value < 2.2e-16 so we reject the null hypothesis that all month 
# have equal people

# Plot histogram of observed vs expected
barplot(rbind(tab, test$expected),
        beside = T,
        xlab = "Month",
        ylab = "Total Attendence",
        ylim = c(0, 180000),
        main = "Gym Attendence",
        legend = c("Observed", "Expected"),
)

Problem 2

options(warn = -1)
# Note: margin made smaller so individual plots do not overlap
par(
  mar = c(2, 1, 1, 1),
  mfrow = c(4, 4)      # 4x4 grid of histograms
)

B <- 10^4
for (s in c(2, 4, 8, 16)) {
  for (k in c(2, 5, 10, 20)) {
    n <- k * s
    test_stat_s_k <- numeric(B)
    for (b in 1:B) {
      # Note: Use sample to generate *discrete* uniform.
      # runif generates a *continuous* uniform sample.
      dat_s_k_b <- sample(1:s, n, replace = T)
      # Convert to factor as some levels might not be present
      tab_s_k <- table(factor(dat_s_k_b, levels = 1:s))
      # Perform test and record the statistic.
      test_stat_s_k[b] <- chisq.test(tab_s_k)$statistic
    }

    # Plot histogram of test statistics
    hist(test_stat_s_k,
      breaks = 100,
      freq = F,
      main = paste0("s = ", s, ", k = ", k),
      type = "l"
    )

    # Overlay the asymptotic (null) density
    curve(dchisq(x, s - 1, ncp = 0, log = F),
      add = T,
      col = "red",
      lwd = 2
    )
  }
}

The usual rule of thumb (k = 5) is doing an okay job in most cases. But its not perfect especially when n is small. Note that this setting of a uniform distribution is the most favorable to the approximation by the chi-squared distribution.
